'''Kevin Bleyer''' is a multiple Emmy award-winning former writer for ''[[The Daily Show with Jon Stewart]]'', a contributor to President Barack Obama's speeches, a co-author of the #1 NY Times Bestseller ''[[Earth (The Book)|Earth: The Book]]'', and a member of the Council on Foreign Relations.

==Television writing==
After doing commentaries and freelance reporting for [[NPR]]'s "[[All Things Considered]]" and American Public Media's "[[Marketplace (radio program)|Marketplace]]", Bleyer began his television writing career as a writer and producer for ''[[Politically Incorrect]]'' from 1996 to 2002.<ref>[http://www.stanfordalumni.org/news/magazine/2006/novdec/dept/bleyer.html]</ref>  He then wrote for the critically acclaimed Bravo series ''[[Significant Others (2004 TV series)|Significant Others]]'' and created and executive produced the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] pilot ''Nightly,'' in which he was also featured as an on-air correspondent.<ref>[http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0088354/]</ref>  In 2003, Bleyer became a writer and producer on ''[[Dennis Miller]]'', a position he held until the show's cancellation in 2005.<ref>[http://www.stanfordalumni.org/news/magazine/2006/novdec/dept/bleyer.html]</ref>

From 2005 to 2012, Bleyer was a member of the writing staff of ''The Daily Show'', where he worked on over 1000 episodes and several specials, earning four [[Emmy]]s in the process.<ref>[http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0088354/]</ref>  He also won a [[WGA Award]] in 2010 for his work on the show in 2009.<ref>[http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0088354/awards]</ref>

Bleyer was also one of several ''Daily Show'' writers to write for the [[80th Annual Academy Awards]] in 2008, when [[Jon Stewart]] served as host.<ref>[http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1103965/]</ref>

==Political writing and activities==
Since 2008, Bleyer has contributed to a number of U.S. President [[Barack Obama]]'s speeches, including the President's addresses at the annual [[White House Correspondents Dinner]] in 2012,<ref>http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-04-30/obama-draws-on-professional-help-to-keep-the-jokes-rolling.html</ref> 2011,<ref>http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/obamas-donald-trump-jokes-helped-184319</ref><ref>http://articles.businessinsider.com/2011-05-03/entertainment/29968910_1_jokes-president-obama-writer</ref> 2010<ref>http://www.thedailybeast.com/blogs-and-stories/2010-05-02/obama-trounces-leno/full/</ref> and 2009.  After the speech in 2010, reporters from several outlets reported erroneously that The Daily Show staff worked on the President's remarks.  The White House and [[Comedy Central]] clarified that Bleyer worked independently on the speech, in light of accusations of the show being too close to President [[Barack Obama]].<ref>[http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/2010/05/04/2010-05-04_jay_leno_recycled_white_house_correspondents_dinner_jokes_daily_show_staffer_wro.html]</ref><ref>[http://www.mediaite.com/tv/obama-whcd-funny-explained-daily-show-writers-penned-jokes/]</ref><ref>http://www.politico.com/click/stories/1005/favreau_on_obamas_whcd_success.html</ref>

Among the first contributors chosen to launch [[The Huffington Post]], Bleyer is a frequent commentator for [[National Public Radio]].  He also reported from Iraq as part of ''The Daily Show'''s "Operation:  Silent Thunder," featuring correspondent [[Rob Riggle]], in 2007.<ref>[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3i26f0065c630ae55db59c86116b0ebb3a]</ref>  That same year, he was profiled by [[Charlie Rose]].<ref>[http://www.charlierose.com/shows/2007/08/11/1/charlie-rose-tomorrow-kevin-bleyer]</ref>

In 2008, Bleyer participated in a mock debate before the [[United States Congress]] based on the [[2007–2008 Writers Guild of America strike]], which involved multiple sitting Congresspeople.<ref>[http://www.campusprogress.org/fieldreport/2440/video-state-of-their-union]</ref>  He also spoke to NPR about his involvement in the strike.<ref>[http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=16981155]</ref>

Bleyer is the author of the book ''Me The People: One Man's Selfless Quest to Rewrite the Constitution of the United States of America'', published by Random House in June 2012.<ref>[http://www.usatoday.com/life/books/news/2009-10-21-josh-lieb_N.htm]</ref>

==Personal life==
Bleyer is the younger brother of sports anchor [[Keith Bleyer]].

Bleyer was raised in [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]] and had a role in the movie ''[[Twice in a Lifetime (film)|Twice in a Lifetime]]'' as a teenager.  He went on to attend [[Stanford University]], where he studied communications and computer engineering and earned a degree in the former in 1994.  He also had an internship at New York's [[Public Theater]], where he assisted playwright [[Anna Deavere Smith]] and performed dramaturgical duties with playwright [[Tony Kushner]].<ref>[http://www.stanfordalumni.org/news/magazine/2006/novdec/dept/bleyer.html]</ref>

He lives in New York.

